article.description: Grant Stout had 17 points, 13 rebounds and six blocked shots and Northern Iowa won its first home game as a ranked team, beating Indiana State 83-56 on Saturday.
article.headline: No. 24 Northern Iowa blows out Indiana State
article.linkText: No. 24 Northern Iowa rolls in first win as ranked team
article.story: CEDAR FALLS, Iowa (AP) -- Northern Iowa coach Greg McDermott has spent the last five years building his program toward a day like Saturday. But as the Panthers were introduced to the home crowd as a ranked team for the first time is school history, even he found it all a little hard to believe. His players made it clear -- early and often -- why the Panthers have entered the Top 25. Grant Stout had 17 points, 13 rebounds and six blocked shots and Northern Iowa (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today; No. 25 AP) pounded Indiana State 83-56. McDermott did a double-take when he heard the public address announcer belt out UNI's ranking during introductions. The purple and gold-clad UNI-Dome crowd greeted the news with a standing ovation, and that's when the magnitude of the school's first national ranking hit McDermott, the architect of the program's rise to national prominence. "It struck me like, 'Wow. We are ranked in the Top 25,'" McDermott said. "It's a neat deal. It's cool for our fans. It's great exposure for our institution, and our league." Travis Brown added a career-high 16 points for the Panthers (20-4, 10-3 Missouri Valley Conference), who hit 16 of their first 22 shots from the field -- including six 3-pointers -- and turned a 20-point first-half lead into their most decisive victory of the season. The opportunity to play in front of their home crowd as a ranked team put an extra bounce in the players' step. They shot a season-high 59 percent and outrebounded the Sycamores 41-24. "It does raise your energy level," guard John Little said. "To finally get to this point, where you're playing at home and being ranked, you really can't take that for granted." Leading by 16 points at halftime, the Panthers blew the game open with a 18-4 run to open the second half. Five players scored during the stretch led by Stout, who hit three baskets in the paint. Brown brought the crowd to its feet with a breakaway dunk, and Little followed with a runner that gave UNI a 65-35 lead with 12:09 left. The Panthers blew a halftime lead and lost 63-55 at Creighton on Tuesday in their first game since entering the Top 25. It was a memory that served the Panthers well as they came out of the locker room at halftime on Saturday. "That was the difference in the game at Creighton Tuesday night. We really got outplayed to start the second half," McDermott said. "We reminded the guys of that at halftime, that we needed to get off to a good start in the second half." The Panthers took a 43-23 lead with a 17-3 run midway through the first half. Little gave UNI a 10-point lead with two 3-pointers, and Brown followed an alley-oop by Stout with a 3 to put the Panthers up by 20. UNI shot 65 percent from the field in the first half and led 47-31. Stout had 11 points, six rebounds and five blocks in the first half, finishing with his fifth double-double in seven games. Little added 11 points for the Panthers. Gabriel Moore scored 10 points for Indiana State (9-12, 2-11), which lost for the 12th time in 13 games. "We did a poor job of finding their shooters. We were concerned about their inside game, and they hit six of nine 3-pointers in the first half and really the game was over," Indiana State coach Royce Waltman said. "You're just not going to win against good teams if you can't defend them." After waiting 26 years to be ranked, UNI's run in the Top 25 might end Monday because of the loss at Creighton. But Saturday's win helped the Panthers reach another milestone -- three straight 20-win seasons for the first time in school history -- and McDermott took solace in the fact that, if only for a week, college basketball fans across the country took notice of the Panthers. "We're one of those 25 teams right now. At least we were for a week," McDermott said. "It's a milestone because it's something that hasn't happened here before, and something that I don't think I would have guessed was possible. But this group has found a way to get it done."
